Anonymous Fri 18 Feb 2022 07:36:58 No.45623082 Report
Quoted By: >>45626581
>>45622419
There are a few other good sci fi stories that delve into hivemind. Unfortunately, I can't quite remember the titles right now. And, some are shorts buried in compilations or lost in magazine issues somewhere.

Another angle that may be related enough to give inspiration is the hivemind of machine AI. The ability of machine intelligence to communicate and reach consensus based up-on data exchange and high-speed communal logic/debate is something that doesn't get enough attention. I think the process is so alien that not many sci fi authors have attempted it, apart from superficially.

Keep an eye open for stories with that theme and you might be able to apply some of it to an insectoid-type hivemind. To some extent, it might be applied to avians. David Brin touched on that a bit with the Gubru in The Uplift War.

And, thinking on it, Star Trek gives numerous examples with how the Borg operate. If you catch old TNG or Voyager episodes that are Borg-heavy, there may be some solid inspiration there. If that's your thing, there are dozens of books that explore Borg collective thinking & dynamics. By mentioning these, I also mean there are good bad examples of what NOT to do.

>Massachusetts
>Daughter of the Codfather
A shark waifur whose the heiress of the codfather. A mafia-like individual who owned dozens of fishing ships that traveled as far as Africa to fish and scallop. Possibly worked with the Latin kings out of New Bedford to smuggle heroine currently causing the states drug epidemic. This waifur would be a rough and tumble lady, yet smart and calculating. She feels like she must follow in her father's footsteps lest she becomes another victim of the state of Massachusetts.
>Bogman's bitch
A dog girl who works at a cranberry bog, shes part Finnish and part cape Verdean. 100% hardworking, shes always willing to wrestle in the mud or go for a swim. She's stuck working at the bog so her family back home can put bread on the table, though the back of her mind she fantasizes about living in a big cape house and having tons of children.
>Town's shipwright
A waifur who works at the local harbour's boat works, building and maintaining catboats or other small sailboats. Shes got muscles from all the work but is the biggest silent nerd you could ever think of. Talking to her she could go on for hours about wooden boats. And also petty politics surrounding their construction from EPA guidelines to town taxes. Shes lonely and older than you, but still within age to have children. But whenever someone mentions it she gets sad and goes back to work, spending hours hewwing and sanding and varnishing until she collapses from overwork.
>The Gull
A waifur stuck in the late 90s-early 2000s, when she would go out drinking and partying, either at a beach bonfire, the local pub or highschool friend's mansion. Staying up until 3am to crawl her way to her one possession, a sailboat on Jackstands in the middle of a storage facility to sleep until it was time to work. Where she would drive a launch and subsist off chips and burgers before work ended. When she would skateboard to the nearest party to the sound of Goldfinger's "superman".

I have been reading a few that I've found through here that do well at making things alien, but I've noticed even when that attempt is made there will always be some familiar assumptions made. Maybe completely non-human biology, but with distinctly humanlike elements of their culture. Or the other way around.
With that said, unique aliens are interesting, but if a sci-fi race is too alien than they won't really fit as an "anthro" for /hmofa/ purposes. We aren't /xeno/, even if there is a lot of overlap.
Alt universe or genetic manipulation is always going to be a more realistic origin for anthros than extra-terrestrial.
That reminds me of one /collared/ flavored story that mixed both. Humans uplifted Earth animals, and then took them to space with them to find true aliens to modify for compatibility and add to our non-human harems.
